is URL, fetch this page\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/read/SKILL.md\\n- request-refactor-plan: Create a detailed refactor plan with tiny commits via user interview, then file it as a GitHub issue\\n  Use when: user wants to plan a refactor, create a refactoring RFC, or break a refactor into safe incremental steps.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/request-refactor-plan/SKILL.md\\n- find-skills: Helps users discover and install agent skills when they ask questions like \\\"how do I do X\\\", \\\"find a skill for X\\\", \\\"is there a skill that can...\\\", or express interest in extending capabilities. This skill should be used when the user is looking for functionality that might exist as an installable skill.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/find-skills/SKILL.md\\n- codebase-design: Shared vocabulary for designing deep modules\\n  Use when: the user wants to design or improve a module's interface, find deepening opportunities, decide where a seam goes, make code more testable or AI-navigable, or when another skill needs the deep-module vocabulary.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/codebase-design/SKILL.md\\n- qa: Interactive QA session where user reports bugs or issues conversationally, and the agent files GitHub issues. Explores the codebase in the background for context and domain language\\n  Use when: user wants to report bugs, do QA, file issues conversationally, or mentions \\\"QA session\\\".\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/qa/SKILL.md\\n- prototype: Build a throwaway prototype to answer a design question\\n  Use when: the user wants to sanity-check whether a state model or logic feels right, or explore what a UI should look like.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/prototype/SKILL.md\\n- resolving-merge-conflicts: Use when you need to resolve an in-progress git merge/rebase conflict.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/resolving-merge-conflicts/SKILL.md\\n- brainstorming: Use when starting creative work, feature design, component design, behavior changes, or broad implementation requests that need intent, constraints, and design clarified before coding.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/brainstorming/SKILL.md\\n- scaffold-exercises: Create exercise directory structures with sections, problems, solutions, and explainers that pass linting\\n  Use when: user wants to scaffold exercises, create exercise stubs, or set up a new course section.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/scaffold-exercises/SKILL.md\\n- design-an-interface: Generate multiple radically different interface designs for a module using parallel sub-agents\\n  Use when: user wants to design an API, explore interface options, compare module shapes, or mentions \\\"design it twice\\\".\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/design-an-interface/SKILL.md\\n- baoyu-slide-deck: Generates professional slide deck images from content. Creates outlines with style instructions, then generates individual slide images\\n  Use when: user asks to \\\"create slides\\\", \\\"make a presentation\\\", \\\"generate deck\\\", \\\"slide deck\\\", or \\\"PPT\\\".\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/baoyu-slide-deck/SKILL.md\\n- baoyu-article-illustrator: Analyzes article structure, identifies positions requiring visual aids, generates illustrations with Type × Style × Palette three-dimension approach\\n  Use when: user asks to \\\"illustrate article\\\", \\\"add images\\\", \\\"generate images for article\\\", or \\\"为文章配图\\\".\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/baoyu-article-illustrator/SKILL.md\\n- check: Reviews code diffs, PRs, issue queues, release readiness, co…\\n  Use when: review, 看看代码, 检查一下, 有没有问题, 是否需要优化, 合并前, 继续优化, 优化代码, 看看issue, 看看PR, release, publish, push, release reaction, GitHub reaction, 发布, 提交, 关闭issue, 发布表情, release表情, close issue, issue close, review my code, check changes, before merge, before rele…\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/check/SKILL.md\\n- tdd: Test-driven development\\n  Use when: the user wants to build features or fix bugs test-first, mentions \\\"red-green-refactor\\\", or wants integration tests.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/tdd/SKILL.md\\n- grilling: Grill the user relentlessly about a plan or design\\n  Use when: the user wants to stress-test a plan before building, or uses any 'grill' trigger phrases.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/grilling/SKILL.md\\n- migrate-to-shoehorn: Migrate test files from `as` type assertions to @total-typescript/shoehorn\\n  Use when: user mentions shoehorn, wants to replace `as` in tests, or needs partial test data.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.agents/skills/migrate-to-shoehorn/SKILL.md\\n- ui-ux-pro-max: UI/UX design intelligence. 50 styles, 21 palettes, 50 font pairings, 20 charts, 9 stacks (React, Next.js, Vue, Svelte, SwiftUI, React Native, Flutter, Tailwind, shadcn/ui). Actions: plan, build, create, design, implement, review, fix, improve, optimize, enhance, refactor, check UI/UX code. Projects: website, landing page, dashboard, admin panel, e-commerce, SaaS, portfolio, blog, mobile app, .h…\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.claude/skills/ui-ux-pro-max/SKILL.md\\n- frontend-design: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces with high design quality\\n  Use when: the user asks to build web components, pages, artifacts, posters, or applications (examples include websites, landing pages, dashboards, React components, HTML/CSS layouts, or when styling/beautifying any web UI). Generates creative, polished code and UI design that avoids generic AI aesthetics.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.claude/skills/frontend-design/SKILL.md\\n- design-taste-frontend: Senior UI/UX Engineer. Architect digital interfaces overriding default LLM biases. Enforces metric-based rules, strict component architecture, CSS hardware acceleration, and balanced design engineering.\\n  Absolute path: /Users/era/.claude/skills/taste-skill/SKILL.md\\n\\n## Connected MCP Servers\\n- context7 (2 tools): Use this server to fetch current documentation whenever the user asks about a library, framework, SDK, API, CLI tool, or cloud service — even well-known ones like React, Next.js, Prisma, Express, Tailwind, Django, or Spring Boot. This includes API syntax, configuration, version migration, library-specific debugging, setup instructions, and CLI tool usage. Use even when you think you know the answer — your training data may not reflect recent changes. Prefer this over web search for library docs. Do not use for: refactoring, writing scripts from scratch, debugging business logic, code review, or general programming concepts.\\n- deepwiki (3 tools): DeepWiki MCP provides AI-powered documentation for GitHub repositories. Available tools: - read_wiki_structure: Get a list of documentation topics for a repository - read_wiki_contents: View full documentation about a repository - ask_question: Ask any question about a repository and get an AI-powered answer - list_available_repos: List your available repositories (private mode only) - generate_wiki: Generate a codebase wiki for a repository — only use when explicitly requested by the user (private mode only) - devin_automation_manage: Manage Devin automations — list, get, create, update, delete, or fetch the trigger event schemas (private mode only) - devin_knowledge_manage: Manage Devin knowledge notes and suggestions — list, search, get, create, update, delete notes, view folder structure, list/view/dismiss knowledge suggestions (private mode only) - devin_playbook_manage: Manage Devin playbooks — list, get, create, update, delete (private mode only) - devin_schedule_manage: Manage scheduled Devin sessions — list, get, create, update, delete (private mode only) - devin_session_create: Create one or more child Devin sessions (private mode only) - devin_session_interact: Manage a Devin session — get status, send messages, sleep/terminate/archive, read messages & attachments, manage tags (private mode only) - devin_session_events: Inspect session events — list summaries, fetch full details, or search event contents (private mode only) - devin_session_search: Search and filter Devin sessions (private mode only) - list_integrations: List all native integrations and MCP servers with their status and settings URLs (private mode only)\\n- mcp-feedback-enhanced (2 tools)\\n- pencil (13 tools): The Pencil MCP server is the editor for reading and writing to .pen files and gives you tools to be an expert design generator and validator specifically for web and mobile applications and websites. - IMPORTANT: The contents of the .pen files are encrypted and can be only access via the \\\"pencil\\\" MCP tools. DO NOT use \\\"Read\\\" or \\\"Grep\\\" tools to read contents of .pen files. - IMPORTANT: Make sure to ONLY use the \\\"pencil\\\" MCP tools when reading or searching contents of .pen files (batch_get) and making changes inside .pen files (batch_design). - IMPORTANT: Always follow the tool definitions and formats for the \\\"pencil\\\" MCP tools. Available tools: - \\\"get_editor_state({ include_schema })\\\": Start with this tool if you are unaware of the current editor state. Use this tool to determine in the beginning of a task, to understand what is the currently active .pen file you want to work on and the current user selection in it and other essential context information. - \\\"open_document(filePathOrNew)\\\": When there is no active editor opened, pass 'new' to create an empty .pen file or if the user explicitly ask to open a specific .pen file use its path to open it. - \\\"get_guidelines(category?, name?, params?)\\\": Load guides and styles for working with .pen files. - \\\"batch_get(patterns, nodeIds)\\\": Retrieve nodes by searching for matching patterns or by reading node ids in batches. Use this for discovering and understand .pen files. - \\\"batch_design(operations)\\\": Use it when designing with .pen files to execute multiple insert/copy/update/replace/move/delete/image operations in a single call. IMPORTANT: MAKE SURE TO FOLLOW THE OPERATION SYNTAX DEFINED IN THE TOOL'S DESCRIPTION. Aim for maximum 25 operations per call—enough to make meaningful progress without overwhelming the system. Available operations (used as a small script where every line a single operation call): - Insert: foo=I(\\\"parent\\\", { ... }) - Copy: baz=C(\\\"nodeid\\\", \\\"parent\\\", { ...}) - Replace: foo2=R(\\\"nodeid1/nodeid2\\\", {...}) - Update: U(foo+\\\"/nodeid\\\", {...}… [truncated]\\n- sequential-thinking (1 tool)\\n- tasks (6 tools)\\nTo use MCP tools, you MUST call `search_tool` first to retrieve the tool's input schema before calling `use_tool`. NEVER guess parameter names — always use the exact schema returned by `search_tool`.\\n</system-reminder>\"}],\"synthetic_reason\":\"system_reminder\"}\n{\"type\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"<system-reminder>\\nMCP servers connected:\\n- context7 (2 tools): Use this server to fetch current documentation whenever the user asks about a library, framework, SDK, API, CLI tool, or cloud service — even well-known ones like React, Next.js, Prisma, Express, Tailwind, Django, or Spring Boot. This includes API syntax, configuration, version migration, library-specific debugging, setup instructions, and CLI tool usage. Use even when you think you know the answer — your training data may not reflect recent changes. Prefer this over web search for library docs. Do not use for: refactoring, writing scripts from scratch, debugging business logic, code review, or general programming concepts.\\n- deepwiki (3 tools): DeepWiki MCP provides AI-powered documentation for GitHub repositories. Available tools: - read_wiki_structure: Get a list of documentation topics for a repository - read_wiki_contents: View full documentation about a repository - ask_question: Ask any question about a repository and get an AI-powered answer - list_available_repos: List your available repositories (private mode only) - generate_wiki: Generate a codebase wiki for a repository — only use when explicitly requested by the user (private mode only) - devin_automation_manage: Manage Devin automations — list, get, create, update, delete, or fetch the trigger event schemas (private mode only) - devin_knowledge_manage: Manage Devin knowledge notes and suggestions — list, search, get, create, update, delete notes, view folder structure, list/view/dismiss knowledge suggestions (private mode only) - devin_playbook_manage: Manage Devin playbooks — list, get, create, update, delete (private mode only) - devin_schedule_manage: Manage scheduled Devin sessions — list, get, create, update, delete (private mode only) - devin_session_create: Create one or more child Devin sessions (private mode only) - devin_session_interact: Manage a Devin session — get status, send messages, sleep/terminate/archive, read messages & attachments, manage tags (private mode only) - devin_session_events: Inspect session events — list summaries, fetch full details, or search event contents (private mode only) - devin_session_search: Search and filter Devin sessions (private mode only) - list_integrations: List all native integrations and MCP servers with their status and settings URLs (private mode only)\\n- mcp-feedback-enhanced (2 tools)\\n- pencil (13 tools): The Pencil MCP server is the editor for reading and writing to .pen files and gives you tools to be an expert design generator and validator specifically for web and mobile applications and websites. - IMPORTANT: The contents of the .pen files are encrypted and can be only access via the \\\"pencil\\\" MCP tools. DO NOT use \\\"Read\\\" or \\\"Grep\\\" tools to read contents of .pen files. - IMPORTANT: Make sure to ONLY use the \\\"pencil\\\" MCP tools when reading or searching contents of .pen files (batch_get) and making changes inside .pen files (batch_design). - IMPORTANT: Always follow the tool definitions and formats for the \\\"pencil\\\" MCP tools. Available tools: - \\\"get_editor_state({ include_schema })\\\": Start with this tool if you are unaware of the current editor state. Use this tool to determine in the beginning of a task, to understand what is the currently active .pen file you want to work on and the current user selection in it and other essential context information. - \\\"open_document(filePathOrNew)\\\": When there is no active editor opened, pass 'new' to create an empty .pen file or if the user explicitly ask to open a specific .pen file use its path to open it. - \\\"get_guidelines(category?, name?, params?)\\\": Load guides and styles for working with .pen files. - \\\"batch_get(patterns, nodeIds)\\\": Retrieve nodes by searching for matching patterns or by reading node ids in batches. Use this for discovering and understand .pen files. - \\\"batch_design(operations)\\\": Use it when designing with .pen files to execute multiple insert/copy/update/replace/move/delete/image operations in a single call. IMPORTANT: MAKE SURE TO FOLLOW THE OPERATION SYNTAX DEFINED IN THE TOOL'S DESCRIPTION. Aim for maximum 25 operations per call—enough to make meaningful progress without overwhelming the system. Available operations (used as a small script where every line a single operation call): - Insert: foo=I(\\\"parent\\\", { ... }) - Copy: baz=C(\\\"nodeid\\\", \\\"parent\\\", { ...}) - Replace: foo2=R(\\\"nodeid1/nodeid2\\\", {...}) - Update: U(foo+\\\"/nodeid\\\", {...}… [truncated]\\n- sequential-thinking (1 tool)\\n- tasks (6 tools)\\n\\nTo use MCP tools, you MUST call `search_tool` first to retrieve the tool's input schema before calling `use_tool`. NEVER guess parameter names — always use the exact schema returned by `search_tool`.\\n</system-reminder>\"}],\"synthetic_reason\":\"system_reminder\"}\n{\"type\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"<user_query>\\n/model grok-4.5 high\\n</user_query>\"}]}\n{\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"id\":\"rs_f4f42cf7-e35d-95a4-b650-2d68b45e5d8f\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"The user is sending a command that looks like they're trying to set the model to \\\"grok-4.5 high\\\". This appears to be a model selection/slash command rather than a software engineering task.\\n\"}],\"encrypted_content\":\"\",\"status\":\"completed\"}\n{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Checking how model selection works in this environment.\",\"tool_calls\":[{\"id\":\"call-b0315064-24aa-468c-b6e7-04260f69009c-0\",\"name\":\"read_file\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_file\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/skills/help/SKILL.md\\\",\\\"limit\\\":80}\"},{\"id\":\"call-b0315064-24aa-468c-b6e7-04260f69009c-1\",\"name\":\"list_dir\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_directory\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide\\\"}\"},{\"id\":\"call-b0315064-24aa-468c-b6e7-04260f69009c-2\",\"name\":\"run_terminal_command\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"command\\\":\\\"ls -la \\\\\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/\\\\\\\" 2>/dev/null; ls \\\\\\\"/Users/era/.grok/docs/user-guide/\\\\\\\" 2>/dev/null | head -50\\\",\\\"description\\\":\\\"List Grok user guide docs\\\"}\"}],\"model_id\":\"grok-4.5\",\"model_fingerprint\":\"fp_a39489019fa99b6e\",\"reasoning_effort\":\"high\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-b0315064-24aa-468c-b6e7-04260f69009c-1\",\"content\":\"- /private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/\\n  - 01-getting-started.md\\n  - 02-authentication.md\\n  - 03-keyboard-shortcuts.md\\n  - 04-slash-commands.md\\n  - 05-configuration.md\\n  - 06-theming.md\\n  - 07-mcp-servers.md\\n  - 08-skills.md\\n  - 09-plugins.md\\n  - 10-hooks.md\\n  - 11-custom-models.md\\n  - 12-project-rules.md\\n  - 13-memory.md\\n  - 14-headless-mode.md\\n  - 15-agent-mode.md\\n  - 16-subagents.md\\n  - 17-sessions.md\\n  - 18-sandbox.md\\n  - 19-plan-mode.md\\n  - 20-background-tasks.md\\n  - 21-terminal-support.md\\n  - 22-permissions-and-safety.md\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-b0315064-24aa-468c-b6e7-04260f69009c-2\",\"content\":\"Tool `run_terminal_command` failed: Terminal error: IO Error: method not found: terminal/create\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-b0315064-24aa-468c-b6e7-04260f69009c-0\",\"content\":\"1→---\\nname: help\\ndescription: >\\n  Grok documentation and configuration help. Use when users ask about\\n  setup, configuration, MCP servers, authentication, skills, slash commands,\\n  keyboard shortcuts, or any Grok feature. Also use proactively when you\\n  detect a user is having trouble with setup or onboarding.\\nmetadata:\\n  short-description: \\\"Grok docs — config, MCP, auth, skills, commands\\\"\\n10→---\\n\\n# Grok Help\\n\\nAnswer the user's question about Grok setup, configuration, or features.\\n\\n## Steps\\n\\n1. If the question is about **current config** (what MCP servers, models, or settings are active),\\n   read `/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/config.toml`. MCP servers are under `[mcp_servers.*]` sections.\\n20→\\n2. If the question is about **how to do something** (setup, adding MCP servers, creating skills,\\n   authentication, keyboard shortcuts, troubleshooting), first check the user-guide docs at\\n   `/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/`. The available guides are:\\n   - `01-getting-started.md` -- Installation, first launch, basic interaction\\n   - `02-authentication.md` -- Browser login, API keys, OIDC, external auth\\n   - `03-keyboard-shortcuts.md` -- Complete key bindings reference\\n   - `04-slash-commands.md` -- All / commands\\n   - `05-configuration.md` -- config.toml, pager.toml, env vars\\n   - `06-theming.md` -- Themes, appearance customization\\n30→   - `07-mcp-servers.md` -- MCP server setup and management\\n   - `08-skills.md` -- Creating and using skills\\n   - `09-plugins.md` -- Plugin marketplace\\n   - `10-hooks.md` -- Lifecycle hooks\\n   - `11-custom-models.md` -- BYOK, Ollama, OpenAI endpoints\\n   - `12-project-rules.md` -- AGENTS.md project rules\\n   - `13-memory.md` -- Cross-session memory\\n   - `14-headless-mode.md` -- CLI scripting and CI/CD\\n   - `15-agent-mode.md` -- ACP/stdio IDE integration\\n   - `16-subagents.md` -- Subagents and personas\\n40→   - `17-sessions.md` -- Session management\\n   - `18-sandbox.md` -- Sandbox mode\\n   - `19-plan-mode.md` -- Plan mode\\n   - `20-background-tasks.md` -- Background tasks and monitoring\\n   - `21-terminal-support.md` -- tmux, SSH, truecolor, clipboard, /terminal-setup\\n   Read the relevant guide(s) for the user's question. If none match, fall back to\\n   `/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/README.md` for the comprehensive reference.\\n\\n3. To **modify config** for the user, edit `/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/config.toml` with search_replace.\\n\\n50→4. To **create a skill** for the user, create `/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`\\n   (read `/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/08-skills.md` for the SKILL.md format).\"}\n{\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"id\":\"rs_f3c8b11b-0ec1-9947-b2b6-286b50579b1d\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"Let me read the slash commands and custom models docs to understand how /model works.\"}],\"encrypted_content\":\"v8SAO09VavjqIw+N7/rbnSZjK7IwcOKITuy6Ee6bkzdLU0lWVAutGd4FYwsDrynCVOobuNxyyXqARkhGVhIoJ3IG1GCna/Iw4spl9Afre6JwxGPc2PPF7nB3+Xk1wZR7j8vFGB7up3Go3P4+T+FrVNM\",\"status\":\"completed\"}\n{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"\",\"tool_calls\":[{\"id\":\"call-8636c92b-3c01-446a-b76f-60768a32e204-3\",\"name\":\"grep\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"pattern\\\":\\\"model|/model\\\",\\\"path\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/04-slash-commands.md\\\"}\"},{\"id\":\"call-8636c92b-3c01-446a-b76f-60768a32e204-4\",\"name\":\"read_file\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_file\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/11-custom-models.md\\\",\\\"limit\\\":100}\"},{\"id\":\"call-8636c92b-3c01-446a-b76f-60768a32e204-5\",\"name\":\"grep\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"pattern\\\":\\\"model|reasoning|high\\\",\\\"path\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/05-configuration.md\\\"}\"}],\"model_id\":\"grok-4.5\",\"model_fingerprint\":\"fp_a39489019fa99b6e\",\"reasoning_effort\":\"high\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-8636c92b-3c01-446a-b76f-60768a32e204-4\",\"content\":\"1→# Custom Models\\n\\nGrok connects to custom model endpoints for alternative providers, self-hosted models, and overriding built-in settings. This guide explains how to select models, configure endpoints, and integrate third-party providers.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Default Models\\n\\nBy default, Grok uses models hosted by xAI, and new sessions start with `grok-build`. Default models require no configuration. Authenticate with `grok login` or an API key, then start a session.\\n10→\\nList all available models:\\n\\n```bash\\ngrok models\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Selecting a Model\\n20→\\n### CLI Flag\\n\\n```bash\\ngrok -p \\\"Hello\\\" -m grok-build\\n```\\n\\n### Slash Command\\n\\nIn the TUI, switch models during a session:\\n30→\\n```\\n/model grok-build\\n```\\n\\nOr use the alias:\\n\\n```\\n/m grok-build\\n```\\n40→\\n### Model Picker (Ctrl+M)\\n\\nPress `Ctrl+M` from the scrollback pane to open the model picker. It lists all available models, both built-in and custom, and lets you switch with a single keystroke. With the prompt focused, `Ctrl+M` toggles multiline input instead -- use `/model` to switch without leaving the prompt.\\n\\n### Config Default\\n\\nSet a persistent default in `~/.grok/config.toml`:\\n\\n```toml\\n50→[models]\\ndefault = \\\"grok-build\\\"\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Supported API Backends\\n\\nGrok supports three API backends. Set `api_backend` in your `[model.*]` config to choose which protocol the model uses:\\n\\n60→| Value | API | Default |\\n|-------|-----|---------|\\n| `\\\"chat_completions\\\"` | OpenAI Chat Completions (`/v1/chat/completions`) | Yes |\\n| `\\\"responses\\\"` | OpenAI Responses (`/v1/responses`) | |\\n| `\\\"messages\\\"` | Anthropic Messages (`/v1/messages`) | |\\n\\nWhen you omit `api_backend`, Grok uses `chat_completions`.\\n\\nTo send provider-specific authentication or version headers -- for example, Anthropic's `x-api-key` -- use the `extra_headers` field described below. Grok sends those headers verbatim with every request to the endpoint.\\n\\n70→---\\n\\n## Configuring Custom Models\\n\\nAdd custom model endpoints in `~/.grok/config.toml` under `[model.<name>]` sections:\\n\\n```toml\\n[model.my-model]\\nmodel = \\\"model-id\\\"                        # Model identifier sent to the API\\nbase_url = \\\"https://api.example.com/v1\\\"   # OpenAI-compatible endpoint\\n80→name = \\\"Display Name\\\"                     # Shown in the model picker\\ndescription = \\\"Model description\\\"          # Optional description\\napi_key = \\\"sk-...\\\"                        # API key for this provider (optional)\\nenv_key = \\\"OPENAI_API_KEY\\\"                # Environment variable holding the API key (optional)\\napi_backend = \\\"chat_completions\\\"          # \\\"chat_completions\\\", \\\"responses\\\", or \\\"messages\\\"\\ntemperature = 0.7                         # Sampling temperature\\ntop_p = 0.95                              # Nucleus sampling parameter\\nmax_completion_tokens = 8192              # Maximum tokens per response\\ncontext_window = 128000                   # Total context window in tokens\\nextra_headers = { \\\"x-api-key\\\" = \\\"sk-...\\\" } # Extra request headers, sent verbatim (optional)\\n90→```\\n\\n### Credential Resolution\\n\\nGrok resolves the API key in this order:\\n\\n1. The `api_key` field in the model config\\n2. The environment variable named by `env_key` (used only if that variable is actually set)\\n3. Your signed-in session token (from `grok login`), for a model with no `api_key`/`env_key` of its own\\n4. The `XAI_API_KEY` environment variable (global fallback; Grok also accepts `GROK_CODE_XAI_API_KEY` for backward compatibility)\\n100→\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-8636c92b-3c01-446a-b76f-60768a32e204-3\",\"content\":\"<workspace_result workspace_path=\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj\\\">\\nFound 8 matching lines\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/04-slash-commands.md\\n55:Show session details including model, turn count, and context usage.\\n138:### `/model <name>`\\n140:Switch to a different model. Accepts model IDs or display names (case-insensitive). For reasoning models you can also pass an effort level as a second argument:\\n143:/model grok-build\\n144:/model Grok Build\\n145:/model Reasoning X high\\n152:Set reasoning effort on the **current** model without re-selecting it. Levels: `low`, `medium`, `high`, `xhigh`. Only works when the active model supports reasoning effort.\\n279:Open the extensions modal on the Hooks tab. From the modal you can view loaded hooks, add or remove custom hooks, and enable or disable them individually. The modal does not grant project trust -- see [10-hooks.md](10-hooks.md) for the trust model.\\n</workspace_result>\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-8636c92b-3c01-446a-b76f-60768a32e204-5\",\"content\":\"<workspace_result workspace_path=\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj\\\">\\nFound 31 matching lines\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/05-configuration.md\\n9:Configuration is resolved in this order (highest priority first):\\n11:1. **CLI flags** (e.g., `--yolo`, `--model`, `--sandbox`)\\n31:[models]\\n32:default = \\\"grok-build\\\"           # model used for new sessions\\n33:web_search = \\\"grok-4.20-multi-agent\\\"   # model used by the web_search tool\\n35:# Defaults applied to every model; a per-model [model.<id>] value always wins.\\n36:# See \\\"Custom Models\\\" for the per-model overrides and full details.\\n48:max_thoughts_width = 120               # max column width for reasoning display\\n62:remote_fetch = true                    # model-catalog + remote-settings fetches from xAI backends (default: true;\\n103:the approval menu highlights one row by default — the cursor row. The\\n233:Add custom model endpoints to use alternative providers or self-hosted models.\\n236:[model.my-model]\\n237:model = \\\"model-id\\\"                    # model identifier sent to API\\n239:name = \\\"Display Name\\\"                 # shown in model picker\\n251:Override built-in models by using their name as the section key:\\n254:[model.grok-build]\\n265:args = [\\\"-y\\\", \\\"@modelcontextprotocol/server-github\\\"]\\n274:args = [\\\"-y\\\", \\\"@modelcontextprotocol/server-postgres\\\", \\\"postgresql://user:pass@localhost/db\\\"]\\n308:model = \\\"embedding-beta-3-small\\\"      # embedding model\\n322:[subagents.models]\\n323:explore = \\\"grok-build\\\"               # route to different models\\n326:To pin the model a subagent uses, set its entry under `[subagents.models]`.\\n356:Each cell can also be toggled via environment variable (highest precedence) or remote feature flag (lowest). See the environment-variables reference for the env var names. Resolution order: env var > config.toml > feature flag > default (on).\\n419:| `title.items` | array | (see above) | Items shown in the title bar. Options: `action-required`, `spinner`, `activity`, `session-name`, `cwd`, `model`, `turn-timer`, `grok`. |\\n518:The same `[telemetry]` table also configures the **external OpenTelemetry stream** — an independent opt-in (it does not require the telemetry toggle above) that ships a curated, content-free usage schema to your *own* OTLP collector. Collector auth is supplied via `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_HEADERS` and is never stored on disk. See [Monitoring & Usage](24-monitoring-usage.md) for the full schema, env vars, and privacy model.\\n544:[models]\\n547:[model.company-grok]\\n548:model = \\\"grok-build\\\"\\n589:mouse_hover = true                    # show hover highlight on the prompt widget\\n628:highlight_overlays_border = false     # highlight extends over selection box border\\n789:When the same server name is defined by more than one source, it is resolved in this order (highest priority first):\\n</workspace_result>\"}\n{\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"id\":\"rs_8dc72637-b933-962a-ae8e-cb4ff8e034f9\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"Based on the documentation, the user ran `/model grok-4.5 high` which is a slash command to switch models. Looking at the docs:\\n\"}],\"encrypted_content\":\"\",\"status\":\"completed\"}\n{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"**Model set:** `grok-4.5` with reasoning effort **high**.\\n\\nI’m ready for your next request.\",\"model_id\":\"grok-4.5\",\"model_fingerprint\":\"fp_a39489019fa99b6e\",\"reasoning_effort\":\"high\"}\n{\"type\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"<user_query>\\n/fork continue here\\n</user_query>\"}]}\n{\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"id\":\"rs_abe9cf51-6553-98d6-bf59-129a1b797339\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"The user is using a `/fork continue here` command. This seems like a session/fork related slash command in Grok. Let me check the documentation for what `/fork` does and what context might exist from ...\"}],\"encrypted_content\":\"\",\"status\":\"completed\"}\n{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"Checking what `/fork` does and recovering prior session context so we can continue.\",\"tool_calls\":[{\"id\":\"call-fecf24c5-330f-420e-9a09-2c1b193b7c8a-6\",\"name\":\"grep\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"pattern\\\":\\\"fork|/fork\\\",\\\"path\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide\\\"}\"},{\"id\":\"call-fecf24c5-330f-420e-9a09-2c1b193b7c8a-7\",\"name\":\"read_file\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_file\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/sessions/%2Fprivate%2Fvar%2Ffolders%2Frb%2Fbzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn%2FT%2F.tmpFSxEpj/019f4fb2-9914-7191-a376-cce109321c40/compaction/INDEX.md\\\",\\\"limit\\\":100}\"},{\"id\":\"call-fecf24c5-330f-420e-9a09-2c1b193b7c8a-8\",\"name\":\"list_dir\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_directory\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj\\\"}\"}],\"model_id\":\"grok-4.5\",\"model_fingerprint\":\"fp_a39489019fa99b6e\",\"reasoning_effort\":\"high\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-fecf24c5-330f-420e-9a09-2c1b193b7c8a-8\",\"content\":\"- /private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/\\n  - README.md\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-fecf24c5-330f-420e-9a09-2c1b193b7c8a-6\",\"content\":\"<workspace_result workspace_path=\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj\\\">\\nFound 16 matching lines\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/04-slash-commands.md\\n71:### `/fork`\\n76:/fork\\n\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/15-agent-mode.md\\n127:| **Session Management**     | `x.ai/session/*`     | `fork`, `resolve_local_for_worktree_resume`      |\\n\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/21-terminal-support.md\\n165:forks) use xterm.js, which only partially implements the Kitty keyboard\\n\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/14-headless-mode.md\\n26:| `--fork-session`        | With `-r`/`-c`, fork into a new session ID instead of appending to the original |\\n179:To carry context across headless calls, use `-r/--resume` or `-c/--continue`. Use `-s/--session-id` only for a **new** session with a **UUID** (errors if not a UUID or already in use under the target directory). Older hidden `-s` upsert/resume behavior is gone — use `-r`/`-c` to continue. With `-r`/`-c`, `-s` requires `--fork-session`:\\n\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/16-subagents.md\\n279:- Title bar inside the frame: status icon (spinner / ✓ / ✗), label + bold description + model, optional \\\"resumed\\\"/\\\"forked\\\" badge, live activity · elapsed time, and [✗] close button.\\n\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/17-sessions.md\\n39:`summary.json` is the index entry. It records the session summary and generated title, the model ID, the creation and update timestamps, the message counts, and a parent session reference for forked or restored sessions. `updates.jsonl` is the authoritative conversation log that drives `/resume` and session restore.\\n81:To switch between, rename, or close the sessions that are currently active (the parent session and any forks), use `/sessions` instead.\\n106:/fork [--worktree|--no-worktree] [directive]\\n109:Pass an optional `directive` to set the new session's first prompt. Use `--worktree` or `--no-worktree` to choose whether the fork runs in a new git worktree; omit both to be asked each time. The `--at <turn>` flag is not supported in this version.\\n198:Use `-s`/`--session-id` only to **create** a new session with a **UUID** (errors if the value is not a UUID, or if that ID already has a session under the target session directory). It does **not** resume an existing session — that was the old hidden upsert behavior; use `-r`/`-c` instead. Combine `-s` with `-r`/`-c` only when also passing `--fork-session` (forks history into a new ID; optional `-s` names the child UUID). This matches Claude Code’s anti-overwrite model (client preflight under the write cwd; sequential use is reliable, concurrent same-ID is best-effort).\\n252:When working with subagents or session forks, Grok can create isolated git worktrees per session. Each worktree gets its own copy of the working directory, so file changes in one session do not affect another.\\n285:- `parent_session_id` -- the source session for a fork or restore\\n\\n/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/05-configuration.md\\n379:fork_worktree_mode = \\\"ask\\\"             # /fork worktree prompt: \\\"ask\\\" | \\\"always\\\" | \\\"never\\\"\\n387:| `fork_worktree_mode` | string | `\\\"ask\\\"` | Worktree prompt for `/fork`: `ask`, `always`, or `never`. |\\n</workspace_result>\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-fecf24c5-330f-420e-9a09-2c1b193b7c8a-7\",\"content\":\"1→# Compaction Segment Index\\n\\n| Segment | File | Turns | Approx bytes | Keywords |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| 000 | segment_000.md | 4 | 24257 | \\\"Producing\\\", \\\"conversation\\\", \\\"compaction\\\", \\\"actions\\\", \\\"commands\\\", \\\"present\\\", \\\"visible\\\", \\\"transcript\\\" |\\n\"}\n{\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"id\":\"rs_4e19d4e4-f4dc-9902-84bb-e1638d9c655e\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"The user forked the session with directive \\\"continue here\\\". Looking at the workspace - it's almost empty, just a README.md. The previous session summary said there was no clear prior task. Let me dig ...\"}],\"encrypted_content\":\"\",\"status\":\"completed\"}\n{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"\",\"tool_calls\":[{\"id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-9\",\"name\":\"read_file\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_file\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/docs/user-guide/04-slash-commands.md\\\",\\\"offset\\\":71,\\\"limit\\\":30}\"},{\"id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-10\",\"name\":\"read_file\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_file\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/README.md\\\"}\"},{\"id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-11\",\"name\":\"list_dir\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_directory\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/sessions\\\"}\"},{\"id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-12\",\"name\":\"read_file\",\"arguments\":\"{\\\"target_file\\\":\\\"/private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/sessions/%2Fprivate%2Fvar%2Ffolders%2Frb%2Fbzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn%2FT%2F.tmpFSxEpj/019f4fb2-9914-7191-a376-cce109321c40/compaction/segment_000.md\\\",\\\"limit\\\":200}\"}],\"model_id\":\"grok-4.5\",\"model_fingerprint\":\"fp_a39489019fa99b6e\",\"reasoning_effort\":\"high\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-11\",\"content\":\"- /private/var/folders/rb/bzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn/T/.tmpFSxEpj/.grok-home/sessions/\\n  - %2Fprivate%2Fvar%2Ffolders%2Frb%2Fbzdrr2hj3x7db9mrc56chs440000gn%2FT%2F.tmpFSxEpj/\\n    - 019f4fb2-9914-7191-a376-cce109321c40/\\n      - announcement_state.json\\n      - chat_history.jsonl\\n      - compaction/\\n        - INDEX.md\\n        - segment_000.md\\n      - compaction_checkpoints/\\n        - d07fe4da-2d8f-4b67-87cb-89628f1952ea.json\\n      - compaction_requests/\\n        - dcace67c-0750-4501-a69c-f2bc6cc2d00f.json\\n      - events.jsonl\\n      - plan.json\\n      - plan_mode.json\\n      - prompt_context.json\\n      - resources_state.json\\n      - rewind_points.jsonl\\n      - signals.json\\n      - summary.json\\n      - summary.json.lock\\n      - system_prompt.txt\\n      - updates.jsonl\\n    - prompt_history.jsonl\\n  - session_search.sqlite\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-10\",\"content\":\"1→agent runtime live grok command workspace\\n\"}\n{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"tool_call_id\":\"call-369bdee3-231b-41fd-bc48-a85772299df4-9\",\"content\":\"71→### `/fork`\\n\\nBranch the current session into a new agent, preserving history up to this point.\\n\\n```\\n/fork\\n```\\n\\n### `/rewind`\\n80→\\nRewind the conversation to an earlier turn, discarding everything after it.\\n\\n```\\n/rewind\\n```\\n\\n### `/copy`\\n\\nCopy the most recent response to the clipboard. Pass a number to copy the Nth-latest response.\\n90→\\n```\\n/copy\\n/copy 2\\n```\\n\\n### `/export`\\n\\nExport the current conversation to a file or the clipboard.\\n\\n100→```\"}\n","total_lines":34}}},"_meta":{"totalTokens":31004,"eventId":"019f4fb2-9914-7191-a376-cce109321c40-328","agentTimestampMs":1783748634331,"promptId":"774514de-59df-46e8-8775-537ab3c280f4","streamStartMs":1783748630545,"turnStartMs":1783748622971,"updateType":"ToolCallUpdate","updateParams":{"toolCallId":"call-09c15479-4cac-4fb6-b5c7-50e79eafabf3-15","status":"Completed"}}}}
